         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">dié</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">堞</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">堞</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="Wade-Giles">tieh</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en" type="preferred">battlements</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-7" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation">battlement</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="en">parapet</term>
            <note>
            	<p>In traditional Chinese fortifications, die refers to the battlements built on the top of a city wall constructed to protect defenders from missile fire. This term appears already in the literature of the Pre-Qin period (e.g. “Mozi, chapter 14, Beiti” : “In the standards of city wall building, the wall should be [built to the] height of 30 feet, die should be added to the top, the width should be ten feet” (行城之法。高城三十尺。上加堞。廣十尺)). The element is also referred to as zhidie, nütouqiang, and duoqiang in different traditional textual sources.</p>
               <p>堞在先秦文獻中就有出現，如《墨子備梯卷十四: 行城之法。高城三十尺。上加堞。廣十尺1。指修築於城墻頂面外邊緣的齒形矮墻。起遮護守城士兵的作用，是城墻頂面的主要防禦設施之壹。又稱雉堞、女頭墻、垛墻等。</p>
               <p>(JIA Tingli 賈亭立 2018, ATTCAT)</p>
            	<p>Related terms: zhidie 雉堞 ; nǚtóuqiáng 女頭墻 ; Duǒkǒu qiáng 垛口墻</p>
               
                <p> Sources and Contributors:</p>
                  <p>槽: 
               (1) 營造法式, 卷31
